The '''Vũng Tàu Charter''' (Hiến chương Vũng Tàu) was a provisional new constitution for [[South Vietnam]] which was introduced on the 16 August 1964 by General [[Nguyễn Khánh]].<ref>Rufus Phillips ''Why Vietnam matters: an eyewitness account of lessons not learned'' 2008 -"Later, at a meeting with [[Maxwell D. Taylor|Ambassador Taylor]] in Vung Tau, Khanh discussed his proposed new constitution. ... to Saigon and proclaimed the new constitution, popularly known as the "Vung Tau Charter," with himself as president."</ref> It was known as the Vũng Tàu Charter from Khanh's preferred coastal residence in [[Vũng Tàu]].<ref>Ken Post ''Revolution, Socialism, and Nationalism in Viet Nam'' 1989 "... that the constitution (known as the Vung Tau Charter from Khanh's preferred coastal residence) was only provisional and ... Doubtless one of his reasons for preferring to be in Vung Tau, whence he could easily escape, on the 24th was the report that the [[Great Viet]] leaders had planned a coup for that day working through [[Trần Thiện Khiêm|General Khiem]], the Minister of Defence."</ref>

The constitution led to the [[Buddhist crisis]], large scale protests in the country led by [[Buddhism in Vietnam|Buddhist]] groups, as the constitution reduced civilian representation in the government, gave Khanh the President's role and  would have allowed press censorship.<ref>Nghia M. Vo ''Saigon: A History'' - Page 146  2011 "The Buddhists demonstrated and demanded the revocation of the Vũng Tàu charter. Under pressure, Khánh gave in to Buddhists' demands. To appease the Buddhists, he had the army remove all its Catholic chaplains. Buddhist [[Trí Quang]] pressured Khánh to give [[Đặng Sỹ]], the Catholic officer who had confronted the Buddhists in Huế, a life sentence. He demanded that [[Ngô Đình Cẩn|Cẩn]], Diệm's brother, be put to death, which Khánh did.7 Street demonstrations continued unabated in September and October, forcing markets, stores, and schools to close and disrupting civilian life."</ref> This led [[Lyndon B. Johnson|President Johnson]] to state that South Vietnam would have to show signs of political cohesion and stability before there would be military intervention against the North.

